  /* Layout: timeline + the sliding INFO TAB -------------------------------- */
  /* The "info tab" is the detail panel that slides out on the right when a bar
     is clicked. (Referred to as the "info tab" throughout; the class names keep
     the older `tl-detail` prefix.) */
  .tl-layout { display: flex; align-items: flex-start; }
  /* Fill the (animating) container so the month columns visibly widen as the
     page grows into the timeline view. The info tab still never resizes the
     timeline: `main`'s width and the info tab's flex-basis transition with the
     SAME duration/easing, so (container − info tab) — this element's width —
     holds constant while the tab slides in. */
  .tl-content { flex: 1 1 auto; min-width: 0; }
  /* The info-tab column is `position: sticky`: scroll well down the timeline,
     click a bar, and the info tab opens at the top of what you're looking at
     right now — not back up at the top of the page. The parent's
     align-items:flex-start keeps this column short while .tl-layout stays as
     tall as the timeline, which is exactly the travel room sticky needs to ride
     down the page with you. The sticky MUST live here (not on the inner panel):
     overflow:hidden — needed to clip the slide-open animation — turns this box
     into the panel's scroll container, so a sticky placed inside it would never
     engage.
       --tl-detail-top is the buffer above the info tab when scrolled to the very
     top (the page header: title + view switch), measured in JS. At rest the tab
     sits at that FULL buffer (normal flow); we pin it at HALF the buffer, so as
     you scroll down the gap eases from the full header height to a tighter
     half-gap and holds there. Falls back to 1rem before/without JS. */
  .tl-detail {
    --tl-detail-w: 360px;
    flex: 0 0 0; overflow: hidden;
    position: sticky; top: calc(var(--tl-detail-top, 1rem) / 2); align-self: flex-start;
    max-height: calc(100vh - var(--tl-detail-top, 1rem) / 2 - 1rem);
    transition: flex-basis 0.55s cubic-bezier(0.4, 0, 0.2, 1);
  }
  /* Fixed px width (not %) so the main timeline boundary never moves when the
     info tab's scrollbar appears/disappears or its content scrolls. */
  .tl-detail.open { flex-basis: var(--tl-detail-w); border-left: 1px solid var(--border); }
  /* The info tab's OWN scroll — independent of the page and the timeline. When
     the details run long, they scroll inside this panel while the sticky column
     above keeps the info tab's top pinned to the viewport.
       The panel is locked to its FINAL open width (the column's flex-basis minus
     its 1px open border) rather than filling the animating container. So the
     content is laid out once at full width and the text never re-wraps as the
     tab opens: the `overflow: hidden` column just reveals more of the
     already-formed panel, making it read as the info tab being pulled out
     instead of slowly unwrapping. */
  .tl-detail-panel {
    width: calc(var(--tl-detail-w) - 1px);
    max-height: calc(100vh - var(--tl-detail-top, 1rem) / 2 - 1rem); overflow-y: auto;
